00:38:16.980 --> 00:38:19.240
So Dan [phonetic]

00:38:19.240 --> 00:38:24.930
has been working with us on
this project that we created

00:38:24.930 --> 00:38:31.280
in collaboration with GetBraille and
Empire Captioning to create a script

00:38:31.280 --> 00:38:36.060
that automatically replaces
the audio track in a video

00:38:36.060 --> 00:38:41.040
with the audio-described audio
track, and lines it with the video

00:38:41.040 --> 00:38:46.260
so that we as blind people can
do that quickly and efficiently.

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:51.460
Most video editing software
by its nature is quite visual

00:38:51.460 --> 00:38:56.100
and does not lend itself to being
used by a screen-reader user.

00:38:56.100 --> 00:38:57.890
And it's also pretty
steep learning curve.

00:38:57.890 --> 00:39:00.920
So we're planning
on launching a class

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:05.910
on teaching audio description
basics sometime in 2024.

00:39:05.910 --> 00:39:09.900
And this command line script
that we're currently using is

00:39:09.900 --> 00:39:16.010
being further developed by Dan
into a graphical user interface.

00:39:17.050 --> 00:39:18.440
That will be like a wizard.

00:39:18.440 --> 00:39:20.829
So you'll be able to
put your video file

00:39:20.830 --> 00:39:22.810
that you want described in there.

00:39:22.810 --> 00:39:28.750
You'll be able to put the timestamps
for the audio description,

00:39:28.750 --> 00:39:31.610
either the audio
description files themselves

00:39:31.610 --> 00:39:35.460
or the audio description text,
and a text-to-speech engine

00:39:35.460 --> 00:39:38.160
will generate those
audio descriptions.

00:39:38.160 --> 00:39:40.030
And then it will
automatically render the video

00:39:40.030 --> 00:39:42.220
in the audio-described format.

00:39:42.220 --> 00:39:47.440
That's coming sometime in 2024,
and we'll keep you guys posted

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:48.970
as that progresses.

00:39:49.900 --> 00:39:55.040
 TANJA: The command line current
process that we have is very,

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:56.040
very cool.

00:39:57.210 --> 00:40:01.700
Essentially, what it is,
we would provide the beginning

00:40:01.700 --> 00:40:06.290
and end timestamps for
however long the clip is going

00:40:06.290 --> 00:40:07.680
to be that gets inserted.

00:40:09.140 --> 00:40:14.690
In a nutshell, the file, when we're
creating the audio description,

00:40:14.690 --> 00:40:17.760
we have to get a sense
of how long we have.

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:23.460
So when we're scripting the
beginning and the end time codes.

00:40:23.460 --> 00:40:28.950
Also, in my process of working
with other vendors in narrating,

00:40:28.950 --> 00:40:33.000
they always provide beginning
and ending time codes for a file.

00:40:34.100 --> 00:40:40.700
They give you a sentence like, Mary
sits in the airport looking glume,

00:40:40.700 --> 00:40:43.520
and you have two seconds to say it.

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:46.300
So you have to make sure
that, timing-wise, it fits,

00:40:46.300 --> 00:40:49.010
and it saves you a lot
of time in that process.

00:40:49.010 --> 00:40:52.850
You can also estimate, while you're
writing, if that's going to fit

00:40:52.850 --> 00:40:53.130
or not.

00:40:53.130 --> 00:40:54.450
So those time codes are imperative.

00:40:55.680 --> 00:41:01.810
The way that this works is we specify
the beginning and ending time code.

00:41:01.810 --> 00:41:06.650
And then we also tell the script,
the local Python Script that we run,

00:41:06.650 --> 00:41:11.020
basically, is this going to be an
extended audio description track,

00:41:11.020 --> 00:41:12.340
or a standard?

00:41:12.340 --> 00:41:16.830
And if it's extended,
it will pause the video and allow

00:41:16.830 --> 00:41:20.540
for the audio-narration
clip, whether that's human

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:28.540
or synthetic to fit in and speak
that line while the video is frozen

00:41:29.730 --> 00:41:30.920
on screen.

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:34.390
So that allows it to kind
of be a smoother process

00:41:34.390 --> 00:41:36.310
for someone viewing the video.

00:41:36.310 --> 00:41:39.940
And we also try to be mindful
of not freezing the video

00:41:39.940 --> 00:41:44.400
at a strange point, [chuckles],
again, for that smooth factor.

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:49.740
A nice way to get timestamps
real quick, just to mention

00:41:51.900 --> 00:41:55.740
for anyone that's wondering,
How do I get a timestamp

00:41:55.740 --> 00:42:00.980
in a video? If you have VLC
media player, for example...

00:42:00.980 --> 00:42:03.010
That’s open-source
just like Audacity.

00:42:03.010 --> 00:42:06.910
You can download that on
Linux, Windows, Mac, et cetera.

00:42:06.910 --> 00:42:08.610
And it's a media player.

00:42:08.610 --> 00:42:12.060
It will play all sorts of
media files, which is handy.

00:42:12.060 --> 00:42:14.670
For example,
you can open an MP4 file

00:42:14.670 --> 00:42:19.960
and you can press the keyboard
shortcut list on Windows,

00:42:19.960 --> 00:42:24.960
Ctrl T, and it will
give you the go-to time.

00:42:26.880 --> 00:42:30.250
Yes, I think it's Ctrl
T, but I can verify that.

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:34.110
It’s a keyboard shortcut that
will just give you an option

00:42:34.110 --> 00:42:37.260
to go anytime in the
video that you'd like to.

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:42.700
But the default value is wherever
you happen to be in the video.

00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:46.570
So it will give you your current
timestamp, and that's very useful

00:42:46.570 --> 00:42:48.740
to write that into your script.

00:42:50.430 --> 00:42:54.960
We're looking into other options
